44–Deceased","1261–Male":"1261–Deceased","1263–Male":"1263–Deceased","1265–Male":"1265–Deceased","1267–Female":"1267–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1218–1242":"1218–1242","1242":"1242","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1261":"1261","Bef 1263":"before 1263","Abt 1240":"about 1240","Bef 1240":"before 1240","Bef 1261":"before 1261","Bef 1267":"before 1267","1267":"1267","Bef 1265":"before 1265","1244":"1244","1265":"1265","1218":"1218","Claverly, Shropshire, England":"Claverley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Of, Claverly, Shropshire, England":"Claverley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Claverley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Claverley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","of, Colemore, Hampshire, England":"Colemore, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Whitmore","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Whitmoor (Devon) or Whitmore (Staffordshire and Dorset), or from any of numerous other places in England with names denoting a white moor or mere (from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>mōr</i> ‘moor’ or <i>mere</i> ‘pool’).","History: Francis Whitmore settled in Cambridge, MA, before 1648."],"variants":[{"name":"Whitemore","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Whitmore  ."]},{"name":"Whittemore","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire): variant of   Whitmore  .","History: Thomas Whittemore came from England to Charlestown, MA, in or <i>c.</i> 1639. Amos Whittemore, born in Cambridge, MA, in 1759 was an inventor and gunsmith, and another Thomas Whittemore was born in Boston in 1800; he was a Universalist clergyman and MA legislator."]},{"name":"Whitmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitmore  .","Americanized form of German   Wittmeyer   or of   Wittmer  ."]},{"name":"Whitmarsh","meanings":["English: habitational name from Whitemarsh, a place in the parish of Sedgehill, Wiltshire, named from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ (i.e. ‘phosphorescent’) + <i>mersc</i> ‘marsh’. Compare   Whitmore  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Whitmore was born about 1240, in England, United Kingdom as the son of Robert Botreaux and Joanna Ballard. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Ada de Walleshall."},"et":{"Abt 1240–":"umbes 1240–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","1261–Male":"1261–Surnud","1263–Male":"1263–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1267–Female":"1267–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1218–1242":"1218–1242","1242":"1242","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1261":"1261","Bef 1263":"enne 1263","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","Bef 1240":"enne 1240","Bef 1261":"enne 1261","Bef 1267":"enne 1267","1267":"1267","Bef 1265":"enne 1265","1244":"1244","1265":"1265","1218":"1218","Claverly, Shropshire, England":"Claverley, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Claverly, Shropshire, England":"Claverley, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Claverley, Shr